SIMPLE: forever
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Forever
<hw>For*ev"er</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧r*⟦ecr⟧v"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>For</ets>, prep. + <ets>ever</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Through eternity; through endless ages; eternally.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>At all times; always.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In England, <xex>for</xex> and <xex>ever</xex> are
usually written and printed as two separate words; but, in the United
States, the general practice is to make but a single word of
them.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Forever and ever</b></col>, <cd>an emphatic
⟦ldquo⟧forever.⟦rdquo⟧</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Constantly; continually; invariably;
unchangeably; incessantly; always; perpetually; unceasingly;
ceaselessly; interminably; everlastingly; endlessly;
eternally.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forevouched</ent>⟦br⟧
